  URL       = {http://circres.ahajournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/74/6/1071},
  abstract  = {A mathematical model of the cardiac ventricular action potential is presented. In our previous work, the membrane \ionNa current and \ionK currents were formulated. The present article focuses on processes that regulate intracellular \ionCa and depend on its concentration. The model presented here for the mammalian ventricular action potential is based mostly on the guinea pig ventricular cell. However, it provides the framework for modeling other types of ventricular cells with appropriate modifications made to account for species differences. The following processes are formulated: \ionCa current through the L-type channel (\I{Ca}), the \ionNa-\ionCa exchanger, \ionCa release and uptake by the sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR), buffering of \ionCa in the SR and in the myoplasm, a \ionCa pump in the sarcolemma, the \ionNa-ionK pump, and a nonspecific \ionCa-activated membrane current. Activation of \I{Ca} is an order of magnitude faster than in previous models. Inactivation of \I{Ca} depends on both the membrane voltage and $[\ionCa+]_i$. SR is divided into two subcompartments, a network SR (NSR) and a junctional SR (JSR). Functionally, \ionCa enters the NSR and translocates to the JSR following a monoexponential function. Release of \ionCa occurs at JSR and can be triggered by two different mechanisms, \ionCa-induced \ionCa release and spontaneous release. The model provides the basis for the study of arrhythmogenic activity of the single myocyte including afterdepolarizations and triggered activity. It can simulate cellular responses under different degrees of \ionCa overload. Such simulations are presented in our accompanying article in this issue of {\em Circulation Research}.},
  refby     = {\cite{joyner:1998, nygren:1998, qu:1999, weiss:1999, rice:1999, spach:2000, rice:2000, tung:2000, joyner:2000, winslow:2000, hund:2000, jafri:1998, wang:2000, qu:2000a}},
