  abstract  = {The action potential model presented in our accompanying article in this journal is used to investigate phenomena that involve dynamic changes of $[\ionCa]_i$, as described below. Delayed afterdepolarizations (DADs) are induced by spontaneous \ionCa release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR), which, in turn, activates both the \ionNa-\ionCa exchanger (\I{NaCa}) and a nonspecific \ionCa-activated current (\I{ns(Ca)}). The relative contributions of \I{NaCa} and of \I{ns(Ca)} to the generation of DADs are different under different degrees of \ionCa overload. Early afterdepolarizations (EADs) can be categorized into two types: (1) plateau EADs, resulting from a secondary activation of the L-type \ionCa current during the plateau of an action potential, and (2) phase-3 EADs, resulting from activation of \I{NaCa} and \I{ns(Ca)} by increased $[\ionCa]_i$ due to spontaneous \ionCa release from the SR during the late repolarization phase. Spontaneous rhythmic activity and triggered activity are caused by spontaneous \ionCa release from the SR under conditions of \ionCa overload. Postextrasystolic potentiation reflects the time delay associated with translocation of \ionCa from network SR to junctional SR. The cell is paced at high frequencies to investigate the long-term effects on the intracellular ionic concentrations.},
